    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p>Not published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>124000</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Χαῖνυς">Χαῖνυς</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Δαμασάνωρ">Δαμασάνορος</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Khainys fils de Damasanôr.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Chainys son of Damasanor.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Chainys figlio di Damasanor.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>Both names are already known at Cyrene with few occurrences, which all belong to men of the upper class, either officers in the army or dedicant
               of the tithe (but for two occurrences of Chainys at Ptolemais in the Roman period).</p>
	<p>The earlier use of the stone with this funerary mention was not mentioned by E. Rosenbaum, who published the relief (see 
	    <bibl><ptr target="#rosenbaum1960"/>, n. <citedRange>284</citedRange></bibl>).</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
